  <p>The Tiger (<span class="chinese-char">虎</span>, hǔ) holds the third position in the Chinese zodiac cycle. In classical Chinese cosmology, the Tiger is associated with the Earthly Branch <strong>Yin (寅)</strong>, representing the hours of 3am to 5am — the moment when darkness begins to yield to the first stirrings of dawn. This is the Tiger's hour: a time of gathering power before the decisive spring into action.</p>
  <p>The Tiger has been revered in Chinese culture since the Shang dynasty, where tiger motifs appear on bronze vessels and oracle bones. The <em>Shanhai Jing</em> (山海經, Classic of Mountains and Seas) describes the white tiger as ruler of the western quadrant, one of the Four Celestial Animals. In the zodiac system, the Tiger's Yang Wood energy represents the explosive force of spring growth — powerful, upward-reaching, and impossible to contain.</p>
</section>

<section id="personality">
  <h2>Personality Traits</h2>
  <p>People born in the Year of the Tiger are characterised by <strong>bravery, confidence, and passionate intensity</strong>. The Tiger's Wood element generates an upward, expansive energy that drives them to lead, compete, and push beyond boundaries that constrain others.</p>

  <h3>Core Strengths</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Bravery</strong> — Tigers confront challenges head-on, rarely shrinking from conflict or risk when they believe in the cause</li>
    <li><strong>Confidence</strong> — A natural self-assurance that inspires others to follow and trust in their vision</li>
    <li><strong>Competitiveness</strong> — Thrives on challenge and rises to peak performance under pressure</li>
    <li><strong>Passion</strong> — When committed to a goal, the Tiger brings an intensity that is both inspiring and formidable</li>
    <li><strong>Charisma</strong> — A magnetic presence that naturally draws attention and commands respect in any room</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Potential Challenges</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Impulsiveness</strong> — The Tiger's bias toward action can lead to decisions made before full consideration</li>
    <li><strong>Unpredictability</strong> — Mood swings and sudden changes of direction can unsettle those around them</li>
    <li><strong>Authority conflicts</strong> — Natural resistance to being controlled or constrained by others' rules</li>
    <li><strong>Overconfidence</strong> — Self-assurance can blind the Tiger to risks or the value of others' counsel</li>
  </ul>
</section>

